Anonymous Wed 16 Oct 2024 14:46:32 No.70023498 Report
Quoted By:
>>70020784
Lots of artists don't seem to have ever looked closely at a picture of a real skunk in the first place. Your picture shows a skunk with countershaded colors. Skunks do not have countershading. They have inverse countershading like honey badgers as a form of aposematism, a visible warning.

Skunks have white on their faces, backs, and tails, in other words, but not normally on their bellies. Lots of animals have lighter colors on their bellies, to conceal them more in shadows. This is called "countershading." It is a gross oversimplification and anthropomorphism, but it is helpful to think of certain species as having high-contrast anti-camouflage markings because they have some kind of defense and "they want everyone to know." It's like wasps with their bright yellow and black strips. Honey badgers and skunks, for example. tl;dr she should have no white markings below her chin and her belly should be completely black. Not many artists draw them tat way, though.
